<section class="card">
  <h2>Manitoba Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Manitoba is a true continental climate: long, cold winters, a fast spring transition,
    strong mid-summer heat, and meaningful early fall frost risk. The season often feels short,
    but heat can accumulate quickly once it arrives.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Spring warms quickly — but frost risk lingers</h3>
  <p>
    May can swing from warm afternoons to near-freezing nights. Planting strictly by daytime
    temperature often leads to setbacks for warm-season crops.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're unsure how frost probability works in planning, this guide explains
    <a href="/guides/what-does-50-percent-frost-probability-mean/">
      what 50% frost probability really means
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Mid-summer heat is your main engine</h3>
  <p>
    June and July can build growing degree days rapidly across southern Manitoba.
    This is when tomatoes, corn, squash, and beans do most of their development.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Short-to-mid season varieties perform most reliably.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Late planting of long-season crops is risky.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Early starts matter.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) The fall window closes decisively</h3>
  <p>
    September frost is common in many regions. Once overnight lows trend downward,
    warm-season crops slow dramatically and may not finish.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're unsure whether a crop will finish in time,
    <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">
      here’s how to estimate maturity before first frost
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Wind and exposure matter</h3>
  <p>
    Prairie winds increase evapotranspiration and can stress young transplants.
    Sheltered sites often perform better than open yards, even within the same town.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Start with your nearest frost and GDD data.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to remaining seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add extra margin if you're in a low-lying frost pocket or exposed prairie site.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Manitoba, conservative planning usually pays off more than pushing the season’s edges.
  </p>
</section>